the rise of Islam--and the Qur'an's appearance as a scripture in its own right--Jews and Christians translated the Hebrew Bible and the Greek New Testament into Arabic for their own use and as a response to the Qur'an's retelling of Biblical narratives. From the ninth century onward, a steady stream of Jewish and Christian translations of the Hebrew Bible and New Testament crossed communal borders to influence the Islamic world. The Bible in Arabic offers a new frame of reference for the pivotal place of Arabic Bible translations in the religious and cultural interactions between Jews, Christians, and Muslims.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAl-Andalus.  aAllusion.  aAlphonse Mingana.  aAnno Domini.  aApocalypse of Peter.  aApologetics.  aArab Christians.  aArabic alphabet.  aArabic script.  aArabic.  aArabs.  aBible translations.  aBible.  aBiblical criticism.  aBook of Job.  aCaliphate.  aCambridge University Press.  aChristian literature.  aChristian scripture.  aChristian theology.  aChristian tradition.  aChristian.  aChristianity and Judaism.  aChristianity.  aChristology.  aChurch of the East.  aClassical Arabic.  aCopts.  aCrucifixion of Jesus.  aDiatessaron.  aEarly Muslim conquests.  aEarly Period.  aEpithet.  aEvocation.  aExegesis.  aGhassanids.  aGod the Father.  aGod.  aHebrew Bible.  aHebrew language.  aIbn Qutaybah.  aIslam.  aIslamic culture.  aIsraelites.  aJewish Christian.  aJewish culture.  aJews.  aJohn the Baptist.  aJudaism.  aKafir.  aLate Antiquity.  aLaw of Moses.  aLectionary.  aLiterature.  aManichaeism.  aMelkite.  aModern Standard Arabic.  aMuslim world.  aMuslim